76561197998264878,Not Recommended,589760,30479363,Posted: 12 March,all,Rayune,"TL;DR version: Decently fun for a few hours if you like tearing apart and fixing cars to min/max one of your own, but needs more content in that area of the game. The driving, on the other hand, is infuriating for anyone who is not a die-hard fan of racing games.I wish I could give this an actual ""mixed"" review, but due to the binary thumbs up/thumbs down of it all, I will give it a thumbs down because of the high price tag.The good:I enjoy buying an old wreck, dismantling it for parts, fixing the parts up, and selling them off. Meanwhile, it's enjoyable to craft a car from all of these parts and occasionally running across some really good engine or gearbox in some old heap that you got for dirt cheap. It can be fun to mix and match parts, and there's a process here that gave me some enjoyment: buy two new factory cars, pick the one that you enjoy driving more, dismantle the other one, and start swapping parts to see if there's maybe some Narnoo suspension that improves how you feel about driving your Wanja. Right now I have a Wanja frame with parts thrown in from a Narnoo, a Buthabang, and a Magura. I promise no degree of accuracy on the spelling of those names, by the way.HOWEVER...The bad:$20 is way too expensive. That is something that I will say right now. It intrigued me, and I enjoyed it for a solid 8 hours, but I don't know how much more I will play it. Meanwhile, I have clocked in about 31 hours on Car Mechanic Simulator 2015, which has a cheaper base price and goes on sale regularly. While it's fun to strip down the cars in this game, it's pretty simplistic when you compare it to Car Mechanic Simulator, and money becomes pretty frivolous once you cross that $100k mark. There is no opportunity to upgrade your abilities, and the interface takes some getting used to before you can really get around things with ease. Furthermore, many of the parts have various numbers listed, but there is no explanation of what they mean. I can understand horsepower and torque as they relate to an engine, but what in the world are these heiroglyphics relating to the suspension? Or how about the steering? Are big numbers good? Are big numbers bad? I know that the answer here is not simple, and that each driver will like things to be different, but it would be helpful to have some in-game indication of what the numbers even MEAN.However, all of these gripes are nothing when you compare it to the driving aspect of the game. I mostly spent time comparing parts on my car just trying to get it to stop feeling like I was driving on BUTTERED ICE. There's simply no way that I am going to be able to control the car well enough to finish any given race, let alone actually winning it. I know that racing a car isn't an easy thing to do, but that doesn't mean that intentionally making things hard to handle adds to realism. It just makes things frustrating. It's still fun for the car building aspect of it, which needs more content, but I hate the driving part of it. Not worth getting at full price unless there are major changes to controls and interface or at least some more content added."
