76561198065827137,Recommended,589760,30430161,Posted: 10 March,all,Gameplay,"I highly recommend this game, particularly for the educational element. You start your journey somewhere in a small village in Australia.This game is very addicting, you get experience, as you gain the in-game experience, you become more and more familiar with parts, ""feel"", damage appearance, and what is most ""cost efficient"" when repairing a car.You have very few diagnostic tools so you are forced to do the diagnostics with visual identification. You can sell them back to the shop for extra money or repair them, you can take on jobs too. If you guys liked Street Legal Racing and my Summer Car you will like this one too.When you finish a race, you get a breakdown of exact lap times, and how you rank against the other racers. This game has more going for it than Car mechanic simulator. Each component can be removed, replaced and swapped between other cars. challenge others to win their cars, or you can just free roam with your car, pull it out of the garage and take if for a spin.Driving the car feels heavy like a real car, I had no lag, game runs very smooth, good tutorial and I like being able to have many different cars to play with at one time. You can set your car up for street racing or dirt. At first it was a little hard to figure out but once you understand the layout and what's going on you start to put cars together pretty fast, No grinding, great sound track. I think there are 6 or 7 different camera angles so that's cool. If you can't find the part you're looking for don't worry it might just be out of stock for a bit, just move on to next part and come back later. You're basically a no name mechanic trying to make a name for him self by building bad♥♥♥♥♥cars that blow everyone else off the race track.This game will get even better as time goes on.My specs incase you where wondering:AMD A8-3870 APU with Radeon HD graphics 3.00 GHz8 GBNot the best, 10 years oldhttp://steamcom